Patch Set 8:

(58 comments)

I had initially added hundreds of comments but I realized partway through doing
that, that it wasn't going to be helpful to have so many similar comments. A
lot of the comments were style-related and since we don't have good tools (yet,
we're working on it) to enforce/fix style issues, I've decided to remove most
of those comments. I might not have removed them all, but I tried to narrow it
down so it was easier not to miss any non-style comments.

For what it's worth, the bulk of the issues I had were (some more important than
others):


 * missing function names. Using:

    function (arguments) {
    }

 without giving the function a name, makes things harder later when we're
 trying to debug a core or a stack trace. I realize some of the existing code
 is missing function names, but it's always good to add them wherever possible.


 * missing curly brackets on if/else:

    if (condition)
        doSomething

 I guess it's personal preference until we codify it, but the rest of /usr/vm
 has tried to always use curly braces for consistency (I noticed you added new
 code both ways here for example).


 * variables sprinkled all over the code. Doing something like:

    function processevent(ev) {
        if (isDone)
            return;

        // filter out events that don't match our predicate (obj)
        if (!objSameValues(obj, ev))
            return;

        self.vs_logger.trace({ev: ev},
            'inspecting possible match from vminfod');

        // loop changes found from vminfod
        (ev.changes || []).forEach(function processChange(change) {
            /*
             * Compare to changes we are looking for.  Return false to remove
             * the item from the changes array (meaning we matched it) or true
             * to keep it in the array (meaning it was not a match).
             *
             * It's possible that there are duplicate changes we are looking
             * for, so only filter out one element per change.
             */
            var hasMatched = false;
            changes = changes.filter(function (wantedArr) {
                if (isDone)
                    return false;

                if (hasMatched)
                    return true;

                if (!Array.isArray(wantedArr))
                    wantedArr = [wantedArr];

                for (var i = 0; i < wantedArr.length; i++) {
                    var match;


 means that the variable "match" at the last line here, is defined several
 levels past the point where its scope actually starts. if instead this we had:

    function processevent(ev) {
        var match;

        ...

 it would make it much more clear what the scope is, and what variables are
 used in this scope.


 * multiple variables defined with a single var:

    var x, y, z;

 is less obvious than:

    var x;
    var y;
    var z;

 even more so when spread across lines like:

    var x, y,
        z;


 * ordering properties in an object. Whenever I see an object or array with a
 bunch of properties like:

    var whatever = {
        greeting: 'hello',
        target: 'world'
    };

 or:

    var whatever = [
        'hello',
        'world'
    ];

 I like to alphabetize them unless there's some other obvious (or documented)
 ordering. This makes it easier when someone else is coming in and adding code
 because they know exactly where to add their new property/element and reduces
 the amount of time they'll need to spend puzzling over why things are ordered
 how they are. There were a lot of examples in this review where properties seem
 to be randomly ordered.

 * Empty blocks like:

    try {
       whatever;
    } catch (e) {
    }

 if we're going to use try/catch, I think the catch block should always contain
 at least a comment explaining why we don't care about the exception. Otherwise
 when someone's reading this code, they'll think that looks like a potential
 error.


All of these style issues I hope we can deal with later however, when we've got
better tools in place, since they don't immediately impact the performance of
vminfod here. The only one that I'd ask you to at least consider doing for now
is adding function names. Since that's work now that will really help us later.


General comments/questions:

 * I didn't review the fswatcher.c file since several other people have already
 gone through that.

 * It's really unfortunate that there's so much reorganizing of the code mixed
 in with code changes. VM.js especially has a lot of reorganizing the code
 without meaningful changes, which made it much more tedious to review than
 it could have been if that refactoring had been a separate CR.

 * I'm a bit worried about the virtual last_modified handling here, as I mention
 in comments in vminfod.js.

 * Have you done any testing to ensure that we're not leaking memory?

 * Do we need some documentation/guidance for Ops as to how vminfod works at a
 high level, and what to do if things go wrong with it or there's suspicion that
 something has gone wrong? Maybe a brief debugging/troubleshooting guide with
 some problems/solutions that you've seen/used while working on this?

 * Have you done testing with a system under heavy I/O and/or CPU load and
 watched the behavior with and without vminfod?

 * Have you run through all the tests with loadManually set?

 * Have you noticed that svc:/smartdc/agent/amon-zoneevents:default in maint on
 emy-12 apparently because unable to connect to vminfod?

 * With vminfod how many more/fewer log messages do we generate when performing
 basic VM operations?

